tural Adaptation to Climatic Extremes in the Canadian Prairies -- tHousehold Access to Capital and Its Influence on Climate-Related Rural Population Change: Lessons from the Dust Bowl Years -- tConclusions -- tPolicy Implications: Panellists’ Comments -- tClimate Change Adaptation Research and Policy for Canadian Agriculture -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn farming systems across Canada, effective risk management is necessary to deal with drought, flooding, and extreme weather, and to adapt to altered climate and weather conditions. Unfortunately, climate change risks and opportunities are not always well understood among researchers and policy makers in the Canadian agri-food sector. This book addresses that gap by providing a wide-ranging synopsis of what climate change means for Canadian agriculture, exploring different approaches to the topic, and presenting examples of current research. It covers all agricultural regions and a wide variety of commodity production and farming systems. This comprehensive survey synthesizes twenty years of research on climate change and Canadian agriculture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgricultural administrationzCanada. 0aAgricultural ecology -- Canada. 0aAgricultural ecologyzCanada. 0aAgriculture -- Management -- Canada. 0aAgriculture and state -- Canada. 0aAgriculture and statezCanada. 0aAgriculturexManagementzCanada. 0aAgriculturezCanadaxManagement. 0aCrops and climate -- Canada. 0aCrops and climate -- Methodology. 0aCrops and climatexMethodology. 0aCrops and climatezCanada. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Agriculture / Sustainable Agriculture.2bisacsh1 aAlila, Younes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/